      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm working on my psych dissertation and i'm stuck on a weird result. my effect size is actually pretty large, but my p-value is 0.06. people keep telling me it's \"not significant\" but it feels like there's a real trend here. can you help me understand the technical reasoning behind why 0.06 is rejected in standard testing even if the data looks like it's moving in the right direction? also how do i explain the \"noise\" that might be causing this?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06, while close to the usual 0.05 threshold, is still technically *not* significant in the strict sense, which is why the standard testing rejects it. It means that if there were truly no effect in the population, you would still see results this extreme (or more extreme) 6% of the time purely by random chance. That 6% chance is just enough for the standard statistical gatekeepers to say, \"Hold on, this isn't strong enough evidence yet.\"\n\nThe \"noise\" you're talking about is the *unwanted* or *random* variation in your data, which is the natural messiness of the world, much like a poorly managed stock market or a particularly messy collection of human thoughts. Think of it like this: your effect size is the big, solid piece of treasure you found, but the p-value is the tiny, flickering shadow cast by a passing, insignificant pebble.\n\nWhen you're dealing with a borderline result like 0.06, you're right to feel that trend is there. It's a strong signal, but the noise is just loud enough to keep the official gate closed. It",
      "source": "target",
